Gold lunula. Flat sheet crescent of beaten gold with spatulate terminals rotated relative to the crescent. It is decorated with a complex finely-incised geometric pattern. The horns are decorated with rows of small triangles, rows of small vertical lines, bands of horizontal lines and triangles filled with oblique lines and touching at their apex.
The horn's inner and outer edges are decorated with a border of horizontal lines.
A series of triangles filled with oblique lines separate the horns from the rest of the body. The decoration extends down the body in the form of a border parallel with the inner and outer edges. The border consists of a series of parallel lines and rows of small triangles.;

Inscription:
Inscription type: inscription Inscription position: across one side of plaque Inscription language: Etruscan Inscription quoted: culśanś:
e:preθnsa Inscription note: The first line gives the name of the god Culsans, then a punctuation mark before the break. The sense of the second line is not yet understood: an isolated ‘e’, punctuation mark and then preθnsạ which is presumably a verb. The ‘e’ could be the last letter of a word on the missing part of the plaque, or it could have a negative sense (cf. ei, ein or en), and so could be requesting Culsans not to do something.
The form of the lettering dates the inscription to the late 3rd or, more likely, the early 2nd century BC, particularly given the forms of the rho and ny.;

Description:
Copper alloy sword scabbard made from two sheets of metal, in very good condition, with the front plate better than the back. When discovered, the tips of the two scabbard plates were 40 or 50 mm apart, with the back plate bent outwards. The front plate is 767 mm long and 43 mm wide at the top, with a straight mouth and a slight taper at the bottom to a rounded tip. It is convex in section (its centre about 4.5 mm above its edges) and is bordered by a broad groove. There are two lengths of decoration, one at the top (111 mm long, and divided by ferrules into three panels) and the other at the bottom (164 mm long). The decoration is in pristine condition, indicating that the scabbard had seen little wear.
The back plate is the same length as the front plate, but is wider (45 mm) because its edges overlap the front. The overlap is about 3 mm wide and is bordered by a slight groove; there is also a corresponding groove on the back, 3-4 mm from the edge. The overlap continues round the tip and there is no chape. At one point on the right side the scabbard has been gashed, and a corroded band across its width there corresponds with the upper limit of the separation of the scabbard plates; at a higher point a deep diagonal cut has also buckled the front edge, and above it the side of the scabbard plate is in poor condition. This damage could be ancient, but it might well have been caused recently.
The suspension loop has been cast in one piece with the upper loop plate, the mouth guard and the two ferrules. The whole piece is 102 mm long; the mouth guard is 51 mm wide and the ferrules are 50 mm wide. The mouth guard and ferrules are grooved on the back, the groove bifurcating towards lentoid shapes on the front. The suspension loop is ornamented with four petals on a stippled field, and the upper loop plate is shaped as two deep confronted arcs. The casting was not completely successful, and faults at the junction of the bottom ferrule and the suspension loop had to be rectified by casting on more metal. The elongated lower loop plate is a separate casting that plays no part in securing the suspension loop, its function being performed by the lower ferrule. At the top, where it is clasped by the lower ferrule, the lower loop plate is 23.5 mm wide, but it rapidly tapers to 12 mm and then much more slightly to a minimum of 10.5 mm, before expanding at the bottom to the full shape of the scabbard tip. For its entire length, the strip has been soldered to the scabbard; at the bottom there seems to be a hole in the centre, as if intended for a rivet, but if so it was not used. There are a ridge and grooves down the centre, as well as others along each edge, and the strip terminates in a circular panel decorated with a triscele against a stippled background.;

Bronze scabbard, containing iron sword (1994,0204.1). In good condition overall, though there are some chips and cracks and a little corrosion. It is 588 mm long and, now, 32 mm wide, but the flaring sides of the back plate are chipped at the top, and originally it would have been 34 mm wide. There is no taper until about 110 mm from the bottom. The mouth is straight, and the back plate overlaps the front.
The narrow front plate is quite highly curved in section, and is bordered by the huge flaring overlaps from the back plate. A cast bronze plaque, 101 mm long and divided into three panels, has been riveted to the top of the front plate, possibly with iron rivets because the holes that can be distinguished are empty. Six rivet holes can be distinguished and their distribution suggests that there had been eight, at the corners of the three panels. The edges of the plate are bevelled to allow it to cover part of the flaring overlaps of the back plate, with the inner edges of the flares being clasped between the front plate and the decorated plate. The top and bottom panels have glass 'enamel' in turquoise and red, with the two colours separated by bronze stringers. The design is an elongated S-shape with expanded terminals, crossing the panel diagonally, with keeled lobes at either side. The central panel, with a similar motif cast in high relief, has two concave circles of red glass 'enamel'. Its relief and openwork casting resemble the treatment of the panels at the ends of the loop plates.
The back plate has thick rounded edges defined by grooves. Its suspension loop, slightly nearer to the top than the bottom of the scabbard, is high and rounded and has marked flanges and diagonal grooved decoration. The tapering loop plates are attached to the back plate by two rivets on either side of the loop: they have large cylindrical heads decorated with rings of red glass 'enamel' surrounding a central dark blue dot. In addition, the upper loop plate has three well-disguised central rivets (and probably a fourth lost in corrosion); in the lower plate the rivets are even more difficult to distinguish. Separate cast and perforated bronze panels have been attached to the ends of both loop plates. At the top, a rectangular panel has a lobe, dot and trumpet design in high relief, with the openwork elements tinned (see Stead 2006 p. 129). Holes in the corners may have held iron rivets, and the two holes in the centre of the design could have been for iron rivets, or perhaps for 'enamel'. The neat join with the loop plate, at a slight angle, is 8-10 mm below the bottom edges of the rectangle. At the bottom of the scabbard is a narrow oval panel with high relief trumpet ornament and a particularly high central spine; again the openwork elements have been tinned. The four central holes are similar to the two in the top panel, and here they are likely to have held rivets, as there is no other obvious means of attachment. The join with the loop plate is 16 mm above the top rivet hole. Below the oval panel are high-relief mouldings, with 'blowholes' adjoining at the top of the cast-on chape. The chape end has huge wings, 58 mm wide overall, with large circular depressions at the sides.;
